00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.240
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:04.240 --> 00:00:08.310
&gt;&gt; Joe Yonana: I couldn't
be more excited

00:00:08.310 --> 00:00:11.240
to introduce Pati Jinich today.

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:17.300
She is a fellow food lover,
writer, PBS television host, and,

00:00:17.300 --> 00:00:21.190
in the interest of full disclosure
as we like to say in newspapers,

00:00:21.190 --> 00:00:25.340
she is a very dear friend
of mine and, honestly,

00:00:25.340 --> 00:00:28.530
one of my favorite
people on the planet.

00:00:28.530 --> 00:00:29.980
And that is the only
time I've ever said

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:31.710
that at The National
Book Festival just

00:00:31.710 --> 00:00:33.930 position:56%
in case you've been to other things.

00:00:33.930 --> 00:00:38.060
I first got to know Pati the way
a lot of people in D.C. have,

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:41.370
by going to one of her
absolutely incredible classes

00:00:41.370 --> 00:00:43.360
at the Mexican Cultural Institute.

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:50.910
Now this was a big class if I
remember, 100, 150 people maybe?

00:00:50.910 --> 00:00:56.420
And as soon as I was
there and I saw Pati start

00:00:56.420 --> 00:01:00.520
to speak I just thought she can
hold the attention of a crowd

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:04.990
like no one I had ever seen, or
at least no one I had ever seen

00:01:04.990 --> 00:01:08.760
who wasn't already a star.

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:12.680
There are naturals and there are
naturals and it seemed obvious

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:14.610
to me that Pati was a natural.

00:01:14.610 --> 00:01:19.450
So I've been so thrilled to see her
audience, the people who have come

00:01:19.450 --> 00:01:23.470
to realize as I already
had amazing she is,

00:01:23.470 --> 00:01:25.830
I've been so thrilled
to see it grow and grow.

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:28.620
She works incredibly hard
to make her PBS show,

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:31.760
"Pati's Mexican Table",
as rich, and complex,

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:34.680
and gorgeous as her home country.

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:38.250
She is passionate about the idea
that American audiences should grow

00:01:38.250 --> 00:01:41.570
to understand just what
Mexican food is all about,

00:01:41.570 --> 00:01:44.550
that it is so different from
region to region of Mexican,

00:01:44.550 --> 00:01:49.550
that it is so full of freshness,
and life, and love, just like Pati.

00:01:49.550 --> 00:01:50.850
&gt;&gt; Pati Jinich: Oh.

00:01:50.850 --> 00:01:52.470
&gt;&gt; Joe Yonana: In her latest
book, "Mexican Today",

00:01:52.470 --> 00:01:55.510
she sets out to prove that
Mexican dishes should be part

00:01:55.510 --> 00:01:58.560
of any modern cook's repertoire.

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:02.300
I've always thought that Pati
has the mind of a scholar,

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:06.740
the soul of a storyteller, the
heart of a mom, and a wife,

00:02:06.740 --> 00:02:10.270
and a friend, and the
smile of a star.

00:02:10.270 --> 00:02:12.510
Please welcome Pati Jinich.

