00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:40.440
So I guess one of the first
things that I'm curious

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:43.150
about is how you feel like your
background, because you have

00:02:43.150 --> 00:02:45.920
such an interesting background,
and I'm not sure everybody knows,

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:50.620
how you feel like your
background led you to food

00:02:50.620 --> 00:02:54.050
and how it continues
to inform what you do?

00:02:54.050 --> 00:02:55.350
&gt;&gt; Pati Jinich: Sure, yeah.

00:02:55.350 --> 00:02:59.970
Well, I think, you know, many
people ask me when I do book talks

00:02:59.970 --> 00:03:04.870
or demos I always get a few people
at the end that want to talk one

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:08.240
on one with me and that ask
me how did you switch careers?

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:10.290
How did you do it?

00:03:10.290 --> 00:03:13.510
And I immediately look into
their eyes and say, "Do it."

00:03:13.510 --> 00:03:14.810
&gt;&gt; Joe Yonana: Mm-hmm.

00:03:14.810 --> 00:03:17.830
&gt;&gt; Pati Jinich: Because I feel like
we all have these personal quests,

00:03:17.830 --> 00:03:20.090
you know, where should
we be, what should we do.

00:03:20.090 --> 00:03:25.970
I happened to have a very early
on existential crisis when I was

00:03:25.970 --> 00:03:30.940
like 30, 33, 34, I was
already the mom of two

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:34.690
and I had been trained
as a political analyst.

00:03:34.690 --> 00:03:39.620
I studied political science in
Mexico and did a three year thesis

00:03:39.620 --> 00:03:43.850
on Mexican federalism, and
democratic institutions,

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:46.270 position:56%
and the different local governments.

00:03:46.270 --> 00:03:48.880
So I was a wealth of
information, you know,

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:53.600
about Mexico all academically
and then I married Danny

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:55.290
who you know, a lovely, lovely man.

00:03:55.290 --> 00:03:56.590
I'm very lucky.

00:03:56.590 --> 00:04:02.090
And we moved to Texas
and it was very weird

00:04:02.090 --> 00:04:05.280
because I felt like I was in limbo.

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:10.250 position:56%
You know the scenery looks a little
bit like Mexico but, Mm, not really.

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:13.380
You went into grocery stores and
you saw jalapeno, you saw avocado,

00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:17.080
you saw it but they
didn't taste like down

00:04:17.080 --> 00:04:18.960
in Mexico and the restaurants -- .

00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:22.190
I got very nostalgic
and started cooking

00:04:22.190 --> 00:04:27.280 position:56%
and very stubbornly continued with
the academic path and did a master's

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:30.610
and working at think tank, all
the while Danny telling me, "Pati,

00:04:30.610 --> 00:04:33.230
change, change, change,
cook, cook, cook."

00:04:33.230 --> 00:04:36.710
And until one day I
just had a crisis.

00:04:36.710 --> 00:04:39.350
I mean, it had been, you know,
as you know, brewing up for

00:04:39.350 --> 00:04:44.810 position:56%
like a year, a year-and-a-half, I
had been so unhappy in my workplace.

00:04:44.810 --> 00:04:48.940
And I'm typically like
a happy person.

00:04:48.940 --> 00:04:50.240
I'm accessible.

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:52.180
I am accommodating.

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:55.480
I'm the youngest one of four
and I'm the one in my family

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:59.360
that people always call for advice
when things are going wrong.

00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:03.070 position:56%
And I'm always the one to say, "Look
at it the other side," you know.

00:05:03.070 --> 00:05:07.660 position:56%
And for a year-and-a-half I hadn't
been able to look at the other side.

00:05:07.660 --> 00:05:09.420
I was miserable.

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:12.700
And I was pregnant with my third

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:17.220
and suddenly I thought what
example am I going to give my kids

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:23.190 position:56%
that they should work like mad to
be fully unhappy twelve hours a day?

00:05:23.190 --> 00:05:27.460
And I resigned and
I felt at that time

00:05:27.460 --> 00:05:29.480
that I was jumping into the abyss.

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:33.640
Like, you know, I had no
training in cooking, no nothing.

00:05:33.640 --> 00:05:38.910 position:56%
And of course loved food and decided
to join L'Academie de Cuisine,

00:05:38.910 --> 00:05:43.210
their night intensive
program, and was loving it

00:05:43.210 --> 00:05:48.930
and suddenly everything that I had
learned in politics, sociology,

00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:53.600
history of Mexico started
to have meaning and started

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:56.250
to like unlock its
real meaning to me

00:05:56.250 --> 00:05:58.700
as I started cooking those recipes.

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:01.690 position:56%
And suddenly everything makes sense.

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:05.150
And, of course, didn't
know, you know,

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:06.450
what I was going to do or what.

00:06:06.450 --> 00:06:09.850
I wanted to start writing
and instead

00:06:09.850 --> 00:06:15.000
of doing policy research papers to,
you know, food writing, you know.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:20.820 position:56%
And I wanted still to be an academic
and of course my dad was very upset

00:06:20.820 --> 00:06:23.570
when I switched careers, as I
know I've told you many times,

00:06:23.570 --> 00:06:26.250
and he was like, "Oh,
after we put you in college

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:28.280
and it was that much money.

00:06:28.280 --> 00:06:33.860
And then your husband paid for
your master's and you're going

00:06:33.860 --> 00:06:36.900
to go rinse pots and pans,"
like it makes no sense.

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:40.830
And I feel at the beginning I
really felt like I was risking,

00:06:40.830 --> 00:06:43.350
like it was a loss, like everything

00:06:43.350 --> 00:06:47.420
that I had done before would just
go, you know, down the chute.

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:51.520
But as years started going
by I realized that everything

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:57.500
